[1]
Date: Mon 10 Nov 2014
Source: La Depeche [in French, trans. CopyEd.LMI, edited]
http://www.ladepeche.pf/L-epidemie-de-chikungunya-continue-de-s-etendre_a1462.html


Chikungunya outbreak continues to spread
----------------------------------------
The chikungunya outbreak continues its progress not only in Tahiti but also in Moorea, Raiatea, Bora Bora, and some atolls of Tuamotu atolls. Due to a low rate of return of surveillance data on suspected and confirmed chikungunya cases, the Institute for Public Health Surveillance cannot provide definite figures concerning these new cases, or estimate the total number of cases in the territory.

However, in order to continue the epidemiological monitoring and allow the targeting of actions that should be implemented, the syndromic surveillance (weekly report of suspicious cases) is the method which must replace the monitoring of biologically confirmed cases. Therefore, all health care professionals are invited to report suspicious cases seen in the week, using the forms from the syndromic surveillance network.

The number of hospitalizations of people diagnosed with confirmed chikungunya is increasing. Since the beginning of the outbreak until the end of week 44, 63 people from both sexes and all ages were hospitalized, mainly in the hospital e ta Taravao (but also Cardella and Uturoa). Hospitalizations are short-term, and are mainly driven by significant pain or the presence of underlying medical conditions, or extreme ages (infants or elderly).

